<tr><td colspan="2"><p align="justify">Monte Burney, a large ice-covered volcano in the Patagonian region of Chile, lies about 200 km NW of the town of Punta Arenas. It was constructed on the western rim of a 6-km-wide caldera, which is partially filled with and surrounded by an unglaciated pyroclastic-flow deposit.  Flank vents produced andesitic-dacitic lava flows and pyroclastic material.  Collapse of the edifice produced a major debris avalanche that traveled to the SSW.  Two large Plinian eruptions have been documented during the Holocene.  The only known historical eruption took place in 1910. </p></td></tr>
