<tr><td colspan="2"><p align="justify">Volcán Lomas Blancas is a small shield-like stratovolcano of late-Pleistocene to Holocene age (Moreno and Naranjo, 1991) located about 15 km SE of Nevado de Longaví. The SE side of the volcano opens from the summit to about 2.3 km, possibly from edifice collapse. The central cone is basaltic. Basaltic-andesite aa lava flows extend 7 km from the collapse scarp. Much of the volcano is covered by pumice deposits that probably originated from Nevado de Longaví.</p></td></tr>
