<tr><td colspan="2"><p align="justify">The conical Bur ni Telong volcano was constructed at the southern base of the massive Bur ni Geureudong volcanic complex, one of the largest in northern Sumatra.  The historically active volcano lies 4.5 km from the summit of Geureudong,and its summit crater has migrated to the ESE, leaving arcuate crater rims.  Lava flows are exposed on the southern flank.  Explosive eruptions were recorded during the 19th and 20th centuries.</p></td></tr>
