<tr><td colspan="2"><p align="justify">Mokuyo Seamount is one of the Shichiyo Seamounts, named for the seven days of the week. Mokuyo ("Thursday") is a basaltic-andesite submarine caldera that rises 1780 m from the sea floor to within less than 1,000 m of the sea surface. The summit caldera is 3 x 2.3 km wide and about 450 m deep and contains a 180-m-high lava dome in its center. Major hydrothermal activity was observed in July 1990, and the volcano was reclassified as active by the Japan Meteorological Agency.</p></td></tr>
