<tr><td colspan="2"><p align="justify">Cherny is a small Quaternary stratovolcano immediately north of the massive Alney-Chashakondzha complex in the central Sredinny Range. An ENE-WSW-trending line of cinder cones was constructed on the western flank of Cherny, which is the southernmost of a cluster of small stratovolcanoes and shields trending NE from Alney-Chashakondzha. Early geological studies in the Sredinny Range (Ogorodov et al., 1972) assigned Holocene ages based on morphology, but later work noted that these volcanoes appear younger because they have less tephra cover than those in eastern Kamchatka. Researchers such as Pevzner (2006) and Ponomareva et al. (2007) do not consider this volcano to be Holocene.</p></td></tr>
