<tr><td colspan="2"><p align="justify">Kebeney is a prominent Quaternary basaltic to basaltic-andesite shield-like volcano in the central Sredinny Range. Two groups of NE-SW-trending cinder cones are on the SW and SE flanks, and other cinder cones are on the NE flank. Lavas surround the small eroded Kalgnitunup cone to the SW. Early geological studies in the Sredinny Range (Ogorodov et al., 1972) assigned Holocene ages based on morphology, but later work noted that these volcanoes appear younger because they have less tephra cover than those in eastern Kamchatka. Researchers such as Pevzner (2006) and Ponomareva et al. (2007) do not consider this volcano to be Holocene.</p></td></tr>
