<tr><td colspan="2"><p align="justify">The 8 x 18 km Koro Island, located between Fiji's Viti Levu and Vanua Levu Islands, is part of the volcanic Lomaiviti Islands. A chain of basaltic cinder cones of late Pleistocene or possibly Holocene age extends NNE-SSW along the crest of the island (Coulson, 1976). The youngest lava flows erupted from those cones on the central plateau, where they form a flat undissected lava field. Young lava flows also reached the sea from one vent location on the west coast.</p></td></tr>
